<!--
    ⚠️ VULNERABLE CONFIGURATION: MASWE-0002 (FileProvider Misconfiguration)

    MASVS:   MASVS-STORAGE-2
    CWE-284: Improper Access Control
    CWE-22:  Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory

    THE VULNERABILITY:
    The <root-path> element maps to the root of the device filesystem ("/").
    This means any content:// URI generated by this FileProvider can reference
    ANY file that this application has read permission to access — including:
      - /data/data/com.hasantuncay.mobsec/shared_prefs/maswe0002_session.xml (auth tokens)
      - /data/data/com.hasantuncay.mobsec/databases/maswe0002_vuln.db (PAN, CVV, MRN)
      - /data/data/com.hasantuncay.mobsec/files/datastore/*.preferences_pb (PII)

    REAL-WORLD IMPACT (HackerOne #876192):
    An attacker app that receives a FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION Intent can request a
    ParcelFileDescriptor via ContentResolver.openInputStream(uri) for any of the above paths.
    If combined with FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION and a path pointing to a native library
    (.so file), the attacker can overwrite it with malicious code → Arbitrary Code Execution.

    MITIGATION (shown in app-secure):
    Replace <root-path> with narrowly scoped paths:
    <files-path name="shared_images" path="images/" />
    <cache-path name="temp_exports" path="net-export/" />

    NEVER use:
      <root-path name="root" path="/" />      ← Exposes entire filesystem
      <files-path name="all" path="." />      ← Exposes all of internal files/
      <external-path name="ext" path="." />   ← Exposes all of external storage
-->
<paths>
    <!-- INTENTIONALLY VULNERABLE: root-path grants access to the entire device filesystem -->
    <root-path
        name="root"
        path="/" />
</paths>
